            {
                id = "specific", speaker = "Maerin",
                text = "*(She blinks — the request disarms her more than any rescue could.)* One unfair, specific, true thing. *(a slow, fierce grin breaks through the fading.)* ...Alright. *(she leans in.)* When I was sixteen, the fishmonger's son — Tobin, sweet boy, dull as a post — gave me a carved fish for my nameday. Spent *weeks* on it. And I told him, in front of *everyone*, that it looked like a *drowned slipper*, and I watched his face *fall*, and I felt — *(she holds your eyes, refusing to flinch)* — I felt *powerful*, and *glad*, and I did *not* apologize, not then, not ever, and he married a kinder girl and I'm *certain* he's happier and I am *still*, dead and fading in the dark, *not sorry.* *(quietly, fiercely.)* *That's* me. Not the grief. Not the cause. A girl who was *cruel to a sweet boy over a carved fish and kept the cruelty her whole short life.* *(she sits back, daring you.)* A symbol can't hold *that.* So if you hold it — if you carry *the drowned slipper* — then you're carrying *me*, and not the smooth dead thing they'll try to make me. Do we have a deal?",
